 382	 <img src="assets/identify-mushrooms.webp" alt="a mushroom on top of a book showing ideas about mushrooms">
 383	 <h3 class="card__title">How can I identify edible mushrooms?</h3>
 384	 <p>Learn from experienced foragers and reliable guidebooks – never rely on apps alone. Study each mushroom's specific features like cap shape, gill structure, stem characteristics, and spore prints. Start with easily identifiable species that have no poisonous lookalikes, and never eat anything unless you're completely certain of its identification.</p>
 385	 </div>
 386	 <div class="card">
 387	 <img src="assets/where-to-find.webp" alt="a mushroom with red cap poking out from a pile of leaves">
 388	 <h3 class="card__title">Where can I find foraging spots?</h3>
 389	 <p>Look in deciduous forests, especially near oak and maple trees, and in damp, shaded areas. Fallen logs and dead trees are often productive spots. Only forage on public lands where it's allowed, and always check local regulations. Remember to get permission for private property and keep your best locations private to prevent over-harvesting.</p>
 390	 </div>
 391	 <div class="card">
 392	 <img src="assets/best-seasons.webp" alt="red cap mushrooms with white dots on it, growing out of a leafy forest">
 393	 <h3 class="card__title">What are the best seasons for mushroom foraging?</h3>
 394	 <p>Spring is ideal for morels, late summer brings chanterelles and boletes, and fall is peak season for most mushrooms including oysters and hen of the woods. Some species can even be found in winter, especially in milder climates. Each season offers different varieties, so year-round foraging is possible.</p>
